Use Case-01 Register Account

Primary Actor: Patient
Description: Allows a patient to create an account using email, password, and profile information.
Preconditions: User does not already have an account.
Postconditions: Patient account is created and verification email is sent.

Basic Flow
Patient opens the registration page.
Patient enters email, password, and profile details.
System validates the input.
System creates the account.
System sends a verification email.
Patient sees a registration success message.
Alternative Flows
3a. If required fields are missing, the system displays validation errors.
3b. If password does not meet complexity rules, the system rejects submission.
4a. If email already exists, the system shows an error message.

Use Case-02 Log In

Actor: Patient / Doctor / Nurse / Administrator / Family Member
Description: Allows authorized users to access the system securely.
Preconditions: User account exists and is active.
Postconditions: User is authenticated and redirected to the appropriate dashboard.

Basic Flow
User opens the login page.
User enters email and password.
System validates credentials.
System creates a session or token.
System redirects the user to the correct dashboard.
Alternative Flows
3a. Invalid credentials cause an error message.
3b. Too many failed attempts temporarily lock the account.
3c. If account is inactive, access is denied.

Use Case-03 Log Vital Signs

Actor: Patient
Description: Allows a patient to record blood pressure, heart rate, temperature, and weight.
Preconditions: Patient is logged in.
Postconditions: Vital signs are saved and checked for abnormalities.

Basic Flow
Patient navigates to the vital entry form.
Patient enters blood pressure, heart rate, temperature, and weight.
Patient submits the form.
System validates the values.
System stores the vital record.
System checks whether the reading is abnormal.
System confirms successful submission.
Alternative Flows
4a. If any field contains invalid data, the system shows validation errors.
5a. If the database is unavailable, the system displays a submission failure message.
6a. If abnormal values are found, the system triggers alert processing.

Use Case-04 View Vital History

Actor: Patient
Description: Allows a patient to view previous vital records over time.
Preconditions: Patient is logged in.
Postconditions: Vital history is displayed in chronological order.

Basic Flow
Patient opens the history page.
System retrieves the patient’s stored vital records.
Patient optionally applies a date range filter.
System displays records in chronological order.
Patient may export the report to PDF.
Alternative Flows
2a. If no records exist, the system displays “No history available.”
3a. If the date range is invalid, the system asks the patient to correct it.
5a. If PDF generation fails, the system shows an error.

Use Case-05 View Patient Dashboard

Actor: Doctor
Supporting Actor: Nurse
Description: Displays all assigned patients and their latest status.
Preconditions: Doctor or nurse is logged in with appropriate permissions.
Postconditions: Dashboard with patient summary data is displayed.

Basic Flow
Doctor opens the dashboard.
System retrieves assigned patients.
System displays patient name, latest reading, and status.
Doctor searches or filters the list if needed.
Doctor selects a patient for further review.
Alternative Flows
2a. If no patients are assigned, the system displays an empty-state message.
3a. If data loading fails, the system shows an error message.
4a. If no search results match, the system informs the user.

Use Case-06 View Patient Vital Trends

Actor: Doctor
Supporting Actor: Nurse
Description: Allows clinical staff to inspect a patient’s vital trends using charts.
Preconditions: User is logged in and has permission to view the patient.
Postconditions: Trend charts are displayed for the selected patient.

Basic Flow
Doctor selects a patient from the dashboard.
System retrieves the patient’s vital history.
Doctor selects a time range such as 7, 30, or 90 days.
System displays charts for each vital type.
Abnormal readings are highlighted.
Alternative Flows
2a. If no data exists for the chosen patient, the system shows a no-data message.
3a. If the selected range contains no records, the system displays an empty chart state.

Use Case-07 Detect Abnormal Readings and Send Alerts

Actor: System
Supporting Actor: Doctor, Email Service
Description: Automatically evaluates submitted vitals and sends alerts when thresholds are exceeded.
Preconditions: A patient has submitted new vital data. Thresholds are configured.
Postconditions: Alert status is recorded and notification is sent when required.

Basic Flow
System receives newly submitted vital data.
System compares values against configured thresholds.
System classifies the reading as Normal, Warning, or Critical.
If Warning or Critical, the system creates an alert record.
System sends an email alert to the responsible doctor.
System records the alert action in the audit log.
Alternative Flows
2a. If no thresholds are configured, default thresholds are used.
5a. If email delivery fails, the system retries and logs the failure.
3a. If reading is Normal, no alert is sent.

Use Case-08 Manage User Accounts

Actor: Administrator
Description: Allows administrators to activate, deactivate, approve, or modify user accounts.
Preconditions: Administrator is logged in.
Postconditions: User account status is updated and the action is logged.

Basic Flow
Administrator opens user management.
System displays all user accounts.
Administrator selects a user account.
Administrator performs an action such as approve, activate, deactivate, or role update.
System saves the change.
System records the action in the audit log.
System displays a success message.
